04482nam a22006495i 9780271084428DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710844287 a10.1515/97802710844282doi  a(DE-B1597)583863  a(OCoLC)1269268503  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR9188.2.M45bC78 2019eb 7aLIT0240602bisacsh04a810.9/3828972231 aCruz, Daniel Shank, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQueering Mennonite Literature :bArchives, Activism, and the Search for Community /cDaniel Shank Cruz. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Building a Queer Mennonite Archive -- t2 Searching for Selfhood in Jan Guenther Braun's Somewhere Else -- t3 Queering Tradition in Jessica Penner's Shaken in the Water -- t4 Stephen Beachy's boneyard, the Martyrs Mirror, and Anabaptist Activism -- t5 The Queer Ethical Body in Corey Redekop's Husk -- t6 Trans Mennonite Literature -- tEpilogue The Future of Queer Mennonite Literature -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough the terms "queer" and "Mennonite" rarely come into theoretical or cultural contact, over the last several decades writers and scholars in the United States and Canada have built a body of queer Mennonite literature that shifts these identities into conversation. In this volume, Daniel Shank Cruz brings this growing genre into a critical focus, bridging the gaps between queer theory, literary criticism, and Mennonite literature.Cruz focuses his analysis on recent Mennonite-authored literary texts that espouse queer theoretical principles, including Christina Penner's Widows of Hamilton House, Wes Funk's Wes Side Story, and Sofia Samatar's Tender. These works argue for the existence of a "queer Mennonite" identity on the basis of shared values: a commitment to social justice, a rejection of binaries, the importance of creative approaches to conflict resolution, and the practice of mutual aid, especially in resisting oppression. Through his analysis, Cruz encourages those engaging with both Mennonite and queer literary criticism to explore the opportunity for conversation and overlap between the two fields.By arguing for engagement between these two identities and highlighting the aspects of Mennonitism that are inherently "queer," Cruz gives much-needed attention to an emerging subfield of Mennonite literature. This volume makes a new and important intervention into the fields of queer theory, literary studies, Mennonite studies, and religious studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexMennonite authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexMennonite authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aQueer theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 21st Century .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271084428zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271084428423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271084428/original  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK